    "summary": "Mudbrick — sun-dried or kiln-fired bricks made from clay, water, and organic temper such as straw — became the dominant building material across the ancient Near East from approximately 8000 BCE onward. The earliest mudbrick structures appear at Pre-Pottery Neolithic sites in northern Syria and southeastern Anatolia, where communities transitioned from pit-house and stone construction to modular brick-based architecture. Mudbrick allowed for flexible, durable, and thermally efficient construction using locally available materials.\n\nThe adoption of mudbrick architecture had profound implications for settlement size, permanence, and social organization. Multi-room houses made from mudbrick could be expanded and modified over time, and their construction required communal effort that likely reinforced social bonds and cooperative labor practices. The subsequent development of mud-brick cities in Mesopotamia, and its widespread use from Egypt to the Indus Valley, reflects how transformative this simple material was in enabling the physical infrastructure of early civilizations.",
